git stash is a temporary save for unfinished work when you're not ready to commit.

Yes, exactly! That's the right way to think about it:

+------------------+--------------------------------+----------------------------------+
|                  | git add + git commit           | git stash                       |
+------------------+--------------------------------+----------------------------------+
| Purpose          | Permanently save to history    | Temporarily save aside          |
+------------------+--------------------------------+----------------------------------+
| When             | Work is done / ready           | Work is incomplete / not ready  |
+------------------+--------------------------------+----------------------------------+
| Visible in log   | Yes                            | No                              |
+------------------+--------------------------------+----------------------------------+

Flow:

Working on feature (incomplete)
        ↓
Need to switch branch urgently
        ↓
Can't commit (code is half-done)
Can't switch (git will warn you)
        ↓
git stash ← saves your incomplete work temporarily
        ↓
Switch branch, do your work
        ↓
Come back
        ↓
git stash pop ← brings your incomplete work back
        ↓
Continue where you left off ✅

--------------------------------------
pop vs apply:

git stash pop → restores and removes from stash list
git stash apply → restores but keeps it in stash list
--------------------------------------------------------
